members.member:
The body's moments of inertia in the local frame. This is like mass, but for rotation: it determines how much torque it takes to rotate the body on each axis. The moment of inertia is usually computed automatically from the mass and the shapes, but this property allows you to set a custom value.
If set to [constant Vector3.ZERO], inertia is automatically computed (default value).
In 3D, the rotational inertia of a body is fully represented by a symmetric 3x3 tensor. The [member inertia] property sets the diagonal entries of this tensor while the off-diagonal entries are set by the [member product_of_inertia] property. For more information on the inertia tensor, see the [url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moment_of_inertia#Inertia_tensor]Wikipedia article[/url].
[b]Note:[/b] This value does not change when inertia is automatically computed. Use [PhysicsServer3D] to get the computed inertia.
[codeblocks]
[gdscript]
@onready var ball = $Ball

func get_ball_inertia():
	return PhysicsServer3D.body_get_direct_state(ball.get_rid()).inverse_inertia.inverse()
[/gdscript]
[csharp]
private RigidBody3D _ball;

public override void _Ready()
{
	_ball = GetNode<RigidBody3D>("Ball");
}

private Vector3 GetBallInertia()
{
	return PhysicsServer3D.BodyGetDirectState(_ball.GetRid()).InverseInertia.Inverse();
}
[/csharp]
[/codeblocks]

The body's products of inertia in (Iyz, Ixz, Ixy) order, resolved in the local frame. In 3D, the full rotational inertia of an object can be represented by a symmetric 3x3 tensor with 6 unique elements. The [member inertia] property sets the diagonal entries while this property sets the off-diagonal entries. When combined with the [member inertia] vector, the local inertia tensor can be fully defined. For most applications, the products of inertia can be left as [constant Vector3.ZERO]. For more information on the inertia tensor, see the [url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moment_of_inertia#Inertia_tensor]Wikipedia article[/url].
If [member inertia] is set to [constant Vector3.ZERO], the body's entire inertia will be computed automatically, and the value set here will be ignored.
If the principal moments and axes of inertia are known, the inertia tensor can be computed by pre- and post-multiplying the principal moments by the principal axes and transpose of the principal axes, respectively. The [member inertia] and [member product_of_inertia] vectors can then be extracted from the inertia tensor.
[codeblocks]
[gdscript]
func inertia_from_principal(principal_inertia: Vector3, principal_axes: Basis):
	var principal_inertia_tensor: Basis = Basis.from_scale(principal_inertia)
	var inertia_tensor: Basis = principal_axes * principal_inertia_tensor * principal_axes.transposed()
	inertia = Vector3(inertia_tensor.x.x, inertia_tensor.y.y, inertia_tensor.z.z)
	product_of_inertia = Vector3(-inertia_tensor.y.z, -inertia_tensor.x.z, -inertia_tensor.x.y)
[/gdscript]
[csharp]
void InertiaFromPrincipal(Vector3 principalInertia, Basis principalAxes)
{
	Basis principalInertiaTensor = Basis.FromScale(principalInertia);
	Basis inertiaTensor = principalAxes * principalInertiaTensor * principalAxes.Transposed();
	Inertia = Vector3(inertiaTensor.X.X, inertiaTensor.Y.Y, inertiaTensor.Z.Z);
	ProductOfInertia = Vector3(-inertiaTensor.Y.Z, -inertiaTensor.X.Z, -inertiaTensor.X.Y);
}
[/csharp]
[/codeblocks]
[b]Note:[/b] The "alternate" convention for products of inertia is used. The products of inertia are assumed to be the positive product of mass and position, and will be negated when inserted into the inertia tensor.
